-- South African Equities: Didata, Datatec, Sun, Merafe, Telkom Are Active
-- Mike Cohen
-- 2010-07-15T15:57:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/south-african-equities-gain-led-by-anglogold-dimension-data-and-datatec.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  gained 31.01, or 0.1 percent, to 27,474.68 in
Johannesburg.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Datatec Ltd.  (DTC SJ), a computer-services company, rose
the most since May 12, adding 1.95 rand, or 6 percent, to 34.60
rand. The company said trading and profitability between March 1
and June 30 continued to improve and that its forecast for
fiscal full-year earnings through Feb 28, 2011, remained
unchanged.  
 Dimension Data Holdings Plc.  (DDT SJ) climbed 2.55 rand, or
22 percent, to 14.12 rand, its biggest advance in more than
seven years. The largest computer-services technology company in
Africa received an offer from Nippon Telegraph & Telephone Corp.
offered 2.1 billion pounds ($3.2 billion).  
 Merafe Resources Ltd.  (MRF SJ), a ferrochrome producer,
rallied the most in more than a week, rising 5 cents, or 3.9
percent, to 1.35 rand. The company said it will report earnings
a share of between 7 cents and 8 cents in the first half from a
loss a year earlier.  
 MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), Africa’s largest mobile-phone
operator, gained 3.05 rand, or 2.8 percent, to 113.05 rand, the
highest price in more than three weeks. MTN will focus on
investor payouts rather than big acquisitions, a “paradigm
shift” in strategy after four failed deals, Chief Executive
Officer  Phuthuma Nhleko  said.  
 Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ), a gold miner, fell the
most since June 17, declining 4 cents, or 4.6 percent, to 83
cents. The company sold 128 million rand ($16.95 million) of
“high-yield, unrated” bonds, Absa Capital, the investment
banking arm of Barclays Plc-owned Absa Group Ltd., said in an e-
mailed statement today.  
 Shoprite Holdings Ltd.  (SHP SJ), South Africa’s biggest
retailer by market value, gained 87 cents, or 1 percent, to
89.12 rand. Sales for the year through June increased 14 percent
to about 67.4 billion rand from a year earlier.  
 Sun International Ltd.  (SUI SJ), South Africa’s biggest
hotel operator, fell the most since June 10, declining 1.79
rand, or 2.1 percent, to 83.21 rand. Sun International, Real
Africa Holdings Ltd. (RAH SJ) and Grand Parade Investments Ltd.
(GPL SJ), which own Cape Town’s GrandWest Casino, called on the
government to reconsider plans for a new casino in the city.
Real Africa was unchanged at 3.50 rand, while Grand Parade
gained 3 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 2.30 rand.  
 Telkom South Africa Ltd.  (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-
line phone company, rose the most since June 22, advancing 65
cents, or 2 percent, to 33.50 rand. Telkom said it will pay U.S.
software maker Telcordia Technologies Inc. $80 million to settle
a nine-year dispute over a canceled contract.  
